}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 214 "3.  Fun
ctions.  In this exericse we study the basic properties of polynomials
 and rational functions.  Some revelant Maple commands will be   facto
r, expand, solve, fsolve, denom, numer, simplify, subs,   ....... ." }
}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 171 "     The first thing we need to learn i
s how to define a function.  There are two ways, each with its own adv
antages and disadvantages.  First define the polynomial p1 as " }
{TEXT 281 2 "a " }{TEXT -1 1 "s" }{TEXT 282 23 "ymbolic expression in \+
x" }{TEXT -1 119 " in the following way:    p1:=x^2-1;  (Note the colo
n before the =, this is always required when defining something.)  " }
}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "p1:=x^2-1;" }}{PARA 11 "" 
1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#>%#p1G,&*$)%\"xG\"\"#\"\"\"F*F*!\"\"" }}}{PARA 0 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 39 "     Now define th
e same polynomial as " }{TEXT 280 30 "an operation on the variable x" 
}{TEXT -1 40 " in the following way:     p2:=x->x^2-1;" }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 13 "p2:=x->
x^2-1;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#>%#p2Gf*6#%\"xG6\"6$%)operat
orG%&arrowGF(,&*$)9$\"\"#\"\"\"F1F1!\"\"F(F(F(" }}}{PARA 257 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 257 "" 1 "" {TEXT -1 190 "Try the following comm
and sequences to see some of the differences in how Maple  treats thes
e two definitions.  As always record your observations and comments on
